	            	                <li class="dsq-comment dsq-clearfix" data-dsq-comment-id="2986017100" id="dsq-comment-2986017100">
	                    <div class="dsq-avatar dsq-tt">
	                        <a href="https://disqus.com/by/weaverryan/">
	                            	                                <img alt="" src="http://a.disquscdn.com/uploads/users/32/6480/avatar92.jpg?1482356913">
	                            	                        </a>
	                    </div>
	                    <div class="dsq-comment-body" id="dsq-comment-body-2986017100">
	                        <div class="dsq-comment-header">
	                            <span class="dsq-comment-date">2016-11-05</span>
	                            <span class="dsq-commenter-name">weaverryan</span>
	                        </div>

	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2986017100" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2986017100" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Roel!</p><p>Hmm! So, a couple of things to try here:</p><p>1) The "404 No Route Found GET /user/create" literally means what it says: this error has nothing to do with security or being denied access. It is actually saying (independent of security) "I don't see any route for /user/create". Try running a <code>bin/console debug:router</code> to see what URLs you have - something must be slightly misconfigured here in your routing configuration.</p><p>2) Once we have (1) figured out (first priority!) then we can "lock" things down with security. The feature that Victor is talking about is mentioned here (it's an older, Symfony 2 tutorial - but this hasn't changed): <a href="http://disq.us/url?url=http%3A%2F%2Fknpuniversity.com%2Fscreencast%2Fsymfony2-ep2%2Fsecure-every-page%3AtobAF5bOq49UmAxlJWvlNMDTV0E&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">http://knpuniversity.com/scree...</a>. Make sure to remove that access_denied_urls thing - that's not needed. Your firewall should look a bit like what Victor posted (<a href="https://disq.us/url?url=https%3A%2F%2Fknpuniversity.com%2Fscreencast%2Fsymfony-security%2Fdeny-access-inside-controller%23comment-2982576414%29%3Arq58iUyFPmfMXJMPn83b8iKoOpE&amp;cuid=1175718" rel="nofollow noopener">https://knpuniversity.com/scre...</a> except after <code>anonymous</code>, you will configure whatever login mechanisms you need (e.g. form_login, guard, http_basic, whatever). You won't have anything under your firewall that actually denies access in any way - that'll happen under access_control. Once you have this, an anonymous user who tries to visit *any* page that requires login will automatically be redirected to /login: that's a natural feature of Symfony (of course, you can configure exactly where they're redirected: but Symfony always redirects the user to the "login" page if it detects that an anonymous user is trying to access a protected page).</p><p>Let us know if that helps! And cheers back!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
	                </li>
